    <stitle>DT-466E and 530E Diesel Engine Diagnostics Model Years 1999-2000 - ELECTRONIC CONTROL SYSTEM DIAGNOSTICS -
        Circuit Function And Diagnostics - Barometric Pressure (BAP) Sensor
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="troubleshoot" graphiccount="3">
        <title>Barometric Pressure (BAP) Sensor</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Signal Functions</title>
            <figure id="f17503022" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figeg1/EG1216A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Function Diagram for Barometric Pressure Sensor</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>The Barometric Pressure (BAP) sensor is a variable capacitance sensor that when supplied with a 5V
                reference signal from the ECM produces a linear analog voltage signal that indicates pressure.
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Timing Control -</emph>
                The BAP signal determines altitude to adjust timing and fuel quantity for improved engine operation and
                smoke control at all altitudes.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Fault Detection / Management</title>
            <para>A BAP signal detected Out of Range High or Out of Range Low by the ECM will cause the ECM to ignore
                the BAP signal and use the Manifold Absolute Pressure (MAP) signal generated at low idle as an
                indication of barometric pressure. If a MAP fault is also detected, the BAP will default to 29.6 in Hg
                (barometric pressure at sea level).
            </para>
            <figure id="f17503023" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figEG1/EG1217A.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="432px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Circuit Diagram for Barometric Pressure Sensor</caption>
            </figure>
