        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Extended Description</title>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Barometric Pressure Sensor (BAP) Operation</emph>
            </para>
            <para>See appropriate circuit diagram:</para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>
                        <hotlnk document="eges1751_98.xml" xrefid="f17503013">Accelerator Position, BAP, and Intake
                            Temperature Sensors
                            <xref refid="f17503013"/>
                        </hotlnk>
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>
                        <hotlnk document="eges1751_98.xml" xrefid="f17503014">Accelerator Position, BAP, and Intake Air
                            Temp , and Dual Drive Cab Circuit Diagram
                            <xref refid="f17503014"/>
                        </hotlnk>
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Accelerator Position, BAP, and Intake Air Temperature Sensor Circuit Diagram for 3000FE
                        Chassis Built January 11, 1999 and After
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Accelerator Position, BAP, Intake Air Temperature Sensor Circuit Diagram for 3000RE Chassis
                        Built January 11, 1999 and After
                    </para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>The ECM sends a regulated 5V signal from the ECM black chassis connector terminal 3 to BAP connector
                terminal B. The BAP sensor returns a variable voltage signal (representing atmospheric pressure) from
                BAP connector terminal C to the ECM at terminal 29. The BAP sensor is grounded from the BAP connector
                terminal A to the ECM signal ground terminal 11.
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">ECM Diagnostics</emph>
            </para>
            <para>The ECM continuously monitors the signal from the BAP sensor to ECM terminal 29. If the signal is out
                of the expected range, a Diagnostic Trouble Code is logged (warning light does NOT turn on) and the ECM
                uses the Manifold Absolute Pressure (MAP) signal generated at low idle to determine barometric pressure.
            </para>
            <para id="f175fc151">
                <emph type="bold">Diagnostic Trouble Code 151</emph>
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">ATA Code PID 108 FMI 3</emph>
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">BAP Signal Out of Range High</emph>
                (
                <emph type="bold">ORH</emph>)
            </para>
            <para>BAP signal greater than 4.95V for more than 1 second.</para>
            <para id="f175fc152">
                <emph type="bold">Diagnostic Trouble Code 152</emph>
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">ATA Code PID 108 FMI 4</emph>
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">BAP Signal Out of Range Low</emph>
                (
                <emph type="bold">ORL</emph>)
            </para>
            <para>BAP signal less than 1.0V for more than 1 second.</para>
